those tranquilizers you gave him.

509
00:32:37,735 --> 00:32:40,300
I don't know what you think you're doing, 
but I'm taking my son and going.

510
00:32:40,335 --> 00:32:45,300
I am not my sister, Paul. 
You do not want to screw with me.

511
00:32:47,800 --> 00:32:51,000
Martha kept a journal.

512
00:32:51,035 --> 00:32:56,000
Every drab event of her drab life, 
meticulously documented.

513
00:32:57,800 --> 00:33:01,600
Including her discovery 
that you and your wife

514
00:33:01,635 --> 00:33:05,500
stole a baby.

515
00:33:05,535 --> 00:33:10,500
A baby named Dana.

516
00:33:14,500 --> 00:33:16,900
I'm sorry if the copies are hard to read.

517
00:33:16,935 --> 00:33:19,300
I hid the originals in a safe place.

518
00:33:19,335 --> 00:33:24,300
It seemed like a reasonable precaution,
since you murdered Martha and all.

519
00:33:25,300 --> 00:33:30,300
Would you like a cookie?

520
00:33:31,300 --> 00:33:34,200
Suit yourself.

521
00:33:34,235 --> 00:33:36,500
Now, I have a little proposition for you.

522
00:33:36,535 --> 00:33:40,900
These are the fantasies of a bored, 
lonely woman. They prove nothing.

523
00:33:40,935 --> 00:33:43,600
The only reason the police haven't caught you yet

524
00:33:43,635 --> 00:33:48,600
is because they have no reason to suspect you.

525
00:33:48,635 --> 00:33:53,600
But once they find out that Martha was 
blackmailing Angela --sorry, Mary Alice--

526
00:33:55,200 --> 00:33:57,200
What it is you want?

527
00:33:57,235 --> 00:33:59,600
The same thing you want.

528
00:33:59,635 --> 00:34:02,700
For you to leave town, 
change your name

529
00:34:02,735 --> 00:34:07,700
and start your life over again
somewhere far away from here.

530
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:11,900
If you're so sure of yourself, 
why don't you just turn me in?

531
00:34:11,935 --> 00:34:14,800
Because Zach would never forgive me.

532
00:34:14,835 --> 00:34:18,200
And it's important that we be on good terms,

533
00:34:18,235 --> 00:34:23,000
seeing as how he's going to 
be living with me now.

534
00:34:23,035 --> 00:34:24,400
What?

535
00:34:24,435 --> 00:34:26,600
You're bad as a parent.

536
00:34:26,635 --> 00:34:30,900
You're about to become a fugitive.
Is that the kind of life you want for your son?

537
00:34:30,935 --> 00:34:35,900
The two of you spending 
every night in a different town?

538
00:34:36,200 --> 00:34:41,200
No. You're a better father than that.

539
00:34:41,400 --> 00:34:46,400
I can't just leave him.

540
00:34:50,500 --> 00:34:54,100
You stole him so that he 
could have a better life.

541
00:34:54,135 --> 00:34:59,000
That was a noble act, Paul. Truly.

542
00:34:59,035 --> 00:35:04,000
And it's time for you to be noble again.

543
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:09,600
Can I at least say goodbye?

544
00:35:09,635 --> 00:35:14,600
Did you allow me to say goodbye to Martha?

545
00:35:42,300 --> 00:35:45,700
Oh, hi. 
I'm looking for Kendra Taylor.

546
00:35:45,735 --> 00:35:48,000
I'm sorry, 
you're going to have to leave.

547
00:35:48,035 --> 00:35:53,000
Oh. You don't understand.
See, I can't just drive away.

548
00:35:53,500 --> 00:35:55,000
Please, back in the car!

549
00:35:55,035 --> 00:35:58,400
Look, um-- Bob.
Let me try to explain.

550
00:35:58,435 --> 00:35:59,500
In the car!

551
00:35:59,535 --> 00:36:04,500
See, this is maybe my last chance to 
find out if I can be with the man I love.

552
00:36:05,100 --> 00:36:06,500
Ma'am--
- And Bob,

553
00:36:06,535 --> 00:36:09,500
I can't begin to tell you 
how much that means to me!

554
00:36:09,535 --> 00:36:14,500
So I'm going to walk up to that house, 
and you're going to let me.

555
00:36:14,535 --> 00:36:16,600
And you know why?

556
00:36:16,635 --> 00:36:21,600
Because behind that badge and that big 
you-could-crush-me-like-a-fly chest,

557
00:36:23,600 --> 00:36:25,900
there's the heart.

558
00:36:25,935 --> 00:36:30,900
A heart that believes in love.

559
00:36:33,800 --> 00:36:35,900
Just get in the damn car!

560
00:36:35,935 --> 00:36:40,000
It's not my fault
you don't have love in your life!

561
00:36:40,035 --> 00:36:42,200
Susan?

562
00:36:42,235 --> 00:36:44,800
Hi, Kendra.

563
00:36:44,835 --> 00:36:48,300
And despite the evidence, despite all 
that's been laid out in front of me,

564
00:36:48,335 --> 00:36:51,000
I just can't help thinking 
there's more to the story.

565
00:36:51,035 --> 00:36:52,500
Does that sound stupid?

566
00:36:52,535 --> 00:36:54,800
No, no. Of course not.

567
00:36:54,835 --> 00:36:59,100
Unfortunately, 
you've got the whole story right here.

568
00:36:59,135 --> 00:37:02,200
Look, Mike's lawyer will probably get self-defense,
and if that's the case--

569
00:37:02,235 --> 00:37:05,700
Delfino sold black tar heroin to my daughter.

570
00:37:05,735 --> 00:37:09,600
He killed the cop who tried to bust him,
got convicted and did his time.

571
00:37:09,635 --> 00:37:11,700
End of story.
- Dad--

572
00:37:11,735 --> 00:37:16,700
She deserves to hear the truth, however awful.

573
00:37:16,800 --> 00:37:21,800
I'm sorry, Ms. Mayer. I really am.

574
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:28,200
I appreciate you talking to me.

575
00:37:30,900 --> 00:37:33,400
What the hell was that?

576
00:37:33,435 --> 00:37:38,100
If she knew the truth,
she'd go running back to him.

577
00:37:38,135 --> 00:37:41,800
She might talk him out of doing this job.

578
00:37:41,835 --> 00:37:46,800
I can't risk that.
Just don't have the time.

579
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:03,400
Quick. Drive around the corner.

580
00:38:03,435 --> 00:38:06,900
We need to talk.

581
00:38:06,935 --> 00:38:07,700
What do you think, Rex?

582
00:38:07,735 --> 00:38:12,500
I'll choose greens. That'll work
whether Gabrielle has a boy or a girl.

583
00:38:12,535 --> 00:38:15,600
That's great.

584
00:38:15,635 --> 00:38:18,500
What's the matter?
You've been mopey all day.

585
00:38:18,535 --> 00:38:22,800
I'm sorry. I'm just worried about the test results.

586
00:38:22,835 --> 00:38:25,600
If they don't find out what's wrong with me soon, 
I'll lose my mind.

587
00:38:25,635 --> 00:38:27,400
Oh honey.

588
00:38:27,435 --> 00:38:30,400
You must get tired of hearing me complain.
- No.

589
00:38:30,435 --> 00:38:31,400
No, not at all.

590
00:38:31,435 --> 00:38:34,000
I think that we should talk about it.

591
00:38:34,035 --> 00:38:38,600
In fact, I think maybe we don't talk enough.

592
00:38:38,635 --> 00:38:41,900
Yeah, I guess.

593
00:38:41,935 --> 00:38:46,100
Why don't we start doing things 
together again as a couple?

594
00:38:46,135 --> 00:38:50,200
Mhm.

595
00:38:50,235 --> 00:38:54,400
I think that as soon as you're well enough,
we should go on a vacation.

596
00:38:54,435 --> 00:38:58,800
Take a trip, go somewhere fun.

597
00:38:58,835 --> 00:39:00,800
Remember our trip to Italy?

598
00:39:00,835 --> 00:39:05,300
Yeah, sort of.
- Sort of?

599
00:39:05,335 --> 00:39:09,500
You don't remember the glorious food
and the gorgeous scenery and--

600
00:39:09,535 --> 00:39:11,500
What I remember is sweating like a pig

601
00:39:11,535 --> 00:39:16,500
and wishing we hadn't spent all our savings.

602
00:39:17,500 --> 00:39:22,500
So where would you like to go?

603
00:39:27,500 --> 00:39:32,500
It doesn't matter. You decide.

604
00:39:37,800 --> 00:39:42,300
Michael wasn't a drug dealer.
- What?

605
00:39:42,335 --> 00:39:44,200
Deirdre was.

606
00:39:44,235 --> 00:39:47,400
Mike-- he kicked the habit earlier on.

607
00:39:47,435 --> 00:39:51,900
But Deirdre couldn't -- 
or didn't want to, I don't know.

608
00:39:51,935 --> 00:39:56,100
Anyway, she spiralled out of control
and was in and out of jail.

609
00:39:56,135 --> 00:39:59,600
One day,
an undercover cop caught her using.

610
00:39:59,635 --> 00:40:04,500
And he forced her
to trade sex for freedom.

611
00:40:04,535 --> 00:40:09,500
Mike found out about it,
and he tried to put a stop to it.

612
00:40:09,900 --> 00:40:14,900
He busted in on the two of them. He--

613
00:40:14,935 --> 00:40:18,500
The cop pulled a gun on him,
and Mike fought him off.

614
00:40:18,535 --> 00:40:22,000
But they both went over a balcony.

615
00:40:22,035 --> 00:40:27,000
Mike was the only one that got back up.

616
00:40:29,700 --> 00:40:33,600
It was self-defense.

617
00:40:33,635 --> 00:40:37,500
Yeah.

618
00:40:37,535 --> 00:40:41,800
Mike went to jail,
trying to save my sister.

619
00:40:41,835 --> 00:40:46,800
But he couldn't.

620
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:52,700
I knew he was good.

621
00:40:52,735 --> 00:40:57,700
I just knew it.

622
00:40:58,700 --> 00:41:03,700
Thank you.

623
00:41:06,600 --> 00:41:11,500
<i>The vow is simple, really.

624
00:41:11,535 --> 00:41:16,500
<i>Those who take it promise
"to stay together, for better or for worse,

625
00:41:17,900 --> 00:41:21,900
<I>"for richer or for poorer,

626
00:41:21,935 --> 00:41:26,900
<I>"in sickness and in health,

627
00:41:27,500 --> 00:41:32,500
<I>"to honor and to cherish,

628
00:41:33,200 --> 00:41:38,200
<I>"forsaking all others

629
00:41:42,100 --> 00:41:47,100
<I>"until death do us part."

630
00:41:52,600 --> 00:41:56,700
<i>Yes, the vow is simple.

631
00:41:56,735 --> 00:42:01,700
<i>Finding someone worthy of such a promise
is the hard part.

632
00:42:02,200 --> 00:42:04,800
<i>But if we can,

633
00:42:04,835 --> 00:42:09,800
<i>that's when we begin
to live happily ever after.

